    "data": {
      "source": "Laboratory experiment (controlled market simulations with human subjects)",
      "wave_or_subset": "Two treatments: UNIFORM (uniform price auction) and FIXED (fixed price offering); 20 rounds per session; roles (3 informed, 1 uninformed) fixed within groups",
      "sample_size": "Groups of 4 bidders (3 informed, 1 uninformed). 14 groups reported for UNIFORM; number of FIXED groups not stated. 20 rounds per group.",
      "unit_of_analysis": "Group-round (market outcomes per group per round); individual bids also recorded",
      "access_details": "not stated",
      "notes": "Supply of 100,000 shares per round. Informed bidders could bid up to 150,000 shares (cost of 5,000 points if informed demand exceeds 100,000); uninformed up to 80,000. UNIFORM: up to six price-quantity bids each (price grid 0\u20136). Market price set at highest price where demand \u2265 supply; if demand \u2264 supply, price = 0. FIXED: price exogenously set to 1.94; pro-rata allocation if oversubscribed. Endowments: UNIFORM\u2014350,000 points (informed), 400,000 (uninformed); FIXED\u2014100,000 (informed), 150,000 (uninformed). Computerized comprehension test used before play."
    },
    "method": {
      "description": "The study uses laboratory experiments to compare revenue and pricing outcomes between uniform price auctions and fixed price offerings for IPOs. Participants, grouped into fours with three informed and one uninformed bidder, repeatedly trade shares under either a uniform-price auction or a fixed-price mechanism. The environment mirrors Biais and Faugeron-Grouzet (2002), including signal structure, capacity constraints, and a cost for informed bidders demanding beyond a threshold. Outcomes such as market price, seller revenue, subscription rates, underpricing, and bidding behavior are recorded and analyzed using nonparametric tests.",
      "steps": [
        "Recruit participants and assign them to groups of four (3 informed, 1 uninformed); maintain roles throughout.",
        "Provide endowments (UNIFORM: 350,000 points informed; 400,000 uninformed. FIXED: 100,000 informed; 150,000 uninformed) and conduct a computerized comprehension test.",
        "Run 20 market rounds per session with supply fixed at 100,000 shares; informed bidders receive high/low signals with equal probability; uninformed receive no signal.",
        "UNIFORM treatment: each bidder submits up to six price-quantity bids on a [0, 6] price grid; determine market price as the highest price where aggregate demand \u2265 supply; allocate shares to bids at/above the clearing price.",
        "FIXED treatment: set price at 1.94; collect quantity demands; allocate pro-rata if oversubscribed, otherwise fill in full.",
        "Apply cost of 5,000 points to an informed bidder if their individual demand exceeds 100,000 units.",
        "Record market price, allocations, earnings, seller revenue, subscription rate, and underpricing each round.",
        "Analyze data using Spearman rank-order correlations and Wilcoxon signed-ranks tests to compare prices to values and revenues across treatments; evaluate frequencies of outcomes consistent with various equilibria (e.g., TCE, EH, EHL, EHU, EHLU)."
      ],
      "models": "Nonparametric statistical tests: Spearman rank-order correlation; Wilcoxon signed-ranks test. Comparisons to theoretical equilibria (TCE, EH, EHL, EHU, EHLU) from BF model.",
      "outcome_variable": "Market price; seller revenue; subscription rate; degree of underpricing; bidder demand quantities by type; alignment with theoretical equilibria",
      "independent_variables": "Auction mechanism (UNIFORM vs FIXED); market value (realized based on signals); bidder type (H, L, U); round",
      "control_variables": "not stated",
      "tools_software": "not stated"
    },
    "results": {
      "summary": "Uniform price auctions generated higher market prices and seller revenues than fixed price offerings. No evidence of tacit collusion equilibria was found. In UNIFORM, market prices rose with market value, underpricing was less frequent, and H-type bidders bid more aggressively and demanded larger quantities than L and U types. Subscription rates were high in both treatments. In FIXED, total demand was often above supply, and bidding by all types fell below theoretical equilibrium predictions, though H and U increased demands over rounds.",
